<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="568" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[811,1457,1164,1321]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">DIAGNOSIS. — Massive multilayered colonies. Autozooecial apertures rounded-polygonal. Autozooecial diaphragms rare to absent in endozone, common in exozone, straight, thin. Vesicles abundant, 4-7 surrounding each aperture, completely isolating autozooecia. Acanthostyles relatively large, 3-6 surrounding each autozooecial aperture. Maculae not observed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[813,1456,1344,1368]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[813,1456,1344,1368]" box="[813,1456,1344,1368]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
ETYMOLOGY. — The species is named after finding it in 
<collectingCountry box="[1352,1452,1344,1368]" name="Argentina" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Argentina</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="568" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[812,1457,1428,1836]" box="[813,957,1428,1454]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[812,1457,1428,1836]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
Massive multilayered colonies.Autozooecia long, having polygonal transverse section in endozone. Autozooecial apertures rounded-polygonal. Autozooecial diaphragms rare to absent in endozone, common in exozone, straight, thin. Vesicles abundant, 4-7 surrounding each aperture, completely isolating autozooecia, angular in cross section, having straight or curved roofs, sealed by calcitic skeleton near colony surface. Acanthostyles relatively large, 3-6 surrounding each autozooecial aperture, originating in endozone, with distinct wide hyaline cores, rarely indenting autozooecia. Autozooecial walls indistinctly laminated, 
<quantity box="[1124,1310,1778,1805]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" unit="mm" value="0.0115" valueMax="0.015" valueMin="0.008">
<geoCoordinate box="[1124,1188,1778,1805]" degrees="0.008" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" precision="55" value="0.008">0.008</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1188,1260,1778,1805]" degrees="0.015" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" precision="55" value="-0.015">-0.015</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
thick. Maculae not observed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[813,1456,1874,2028]" box="[813,957,1874,1900]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">COMPARISON</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="570" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[813,1456,1874,2028]" lastBlockId="9.[131,776,215,624]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="570" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">
The investigated material is similar to representatives of the Family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Utgaard" authorityYear="1983" box="[891,1036,1937,1963]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="family">Xenotrypidae</taxonomicName>
which consists of two genera: 
<taxonomicName authority="Bassler, 1952" authorityName="Bassler" authorityYear="1952" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1350,1454,1938,1963]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Xenotrypa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BASSLER R. S." box="[813,957,1969,1996]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" pagination="381 - 385" refId="ref18772" refString="BASSLER R. S. 1952. - Taxonomic notes on genera of fossil and Recent Bryozoa. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences 42: 381 - 385. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 24531385" type="journal article" year="1952">Bassler, 1952</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bassler, 1952" authorityName="Bassler" authorityYear="1952" box="[1017,1306,1969,1996]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Hennigopora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1017,1151,1970,1995]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Hennigopora</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BASSLER R. S." box="[1158,1306,1969,1996]" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" pagination="381 - 385" refId="ref18772" refString="BASSLER R. S. 1952. - Taxonomic notes on genera of fossil and Recent Bryozoa. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences 42: 381 - 385. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 24531385" type="journal article" year="1952">Bassler, 1952</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, its assignment to a genus is difficult. The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Bassler, 1952" authorityName="Bassler" authorityYear="1952" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="570" order="Cystoporida" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1269,1371,2002,2027]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="568">Xenotrypa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BASSLER R. S." lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="570" pageId="7" pageNumber="568" pagination="381 - 385" refId="ref18772" refString="BASSLER R. S. 1952. - Taxonomic notes on genera of fossil and Recent Bryozoa. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences 42: 381 - 385. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 24531385" type="journal article" year="1952">Bassler, 1952</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is known with few specimens restricted mainly to the 
<typeStatus box="[133,179,248,274]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">type</typeStatus>
material of two species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bassler, 1911)" baseAuthorityName="Bassler" baseAuthorityYear="1911" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="primaeva">
<emphasis box="[567,774,248,273]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Xenotrypa primaeva</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="BASSLER R. S." box="[139,287,279,305]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" pagination="1 - 382" refId="ref18727" refString="BASSLER R. S. 1911. - The early Paleozoic Bryozoa of the Baltic Provinces. Bulletin of the Smithsonian Institution, United States National Museum 77: 1 - 382. https: // hdl. handle. net / 10088 / 30445" type="journal article" year="1911">Bassler, 1911</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Lower Ordovician of 
<collectingCountry box="[649,721,279,305]" name="Russia" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Russia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Astrova, 1965" authorityName="Astrova" authorityYear="1965" box="[134,409,311,338]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Constellariidae" genus="Lunaferamita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="bassleri">
<emphasis box="[134,244,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">X. bassleri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="ASTROVA G. G." box="[252,409,311,338]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" pagination="1 - 432" refId="ref18571" refString="ASTROVA G. G. 1965. - Morphology, history of development and system of the Ordovician and Silurian Bryozoa. Trudy Paleontologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR 106: 1 - 432 [in Russian]." type="journal article" year="1965">Astrova, 1965</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Middle Ordovician of 
<collectingCountry box="[134,207,343,369]" name="Russia" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Russia</collectingCountry>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[269,315,343,369]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bassler" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[405,534,344,369]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="primaeva">
<emphasis box="[405,534,344,369]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">X. primaeva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reveals large acanthostyles with centres of dark colour (
<bibRefCitation author="UTGAARD J." box="[515,728,375,401]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" pagination="357 - 439" refId="ref23420" refString="UTGAARD J. 1983. - Systematic descriptions for the Order Cystoporata, in ROBISON R. A., (ed), Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology. Part G (1): Bryozoa (revised). Geological Society of America and University of Kansas Press, Boulder: 357 - 439." type="book chapter" year="1983">Utgaard 1983: 377</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 169). In contrast, acanthostyles in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bassler" authorityYear="1952" box="[499,632,407,432]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Hennigopora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[499,632,407,432]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Hennigopora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have distinct hyaline cores, like in present material. 
<taxonomicName authority="Ernst &amp; Carrera, 2022" authorityName="Ernst &amp; Carrera" authorityYear="2022" box="[532,775,439,464]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="argentinensis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[532,775,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Xenotrypa argentinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[132,192,471,497]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bassler" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[336,465,471,496]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="primaeva">
<emphasis box="[336,465,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">X. primaeva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Astrova" authorityYear="1965" box="[521,627,470,496]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Constellariidae" genus="Lunaferamita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="bassleri">
<emphasis box="[521,627,470,496]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">X. bassleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its smaller autozooecial apertures (aperture width at average 
<quantity box="[675,776,502,529]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="0.16">0.16 mm</quantity>
vs 
<quantity box="[160,259,534,561]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5999999999999996" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="0.36">0.36 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bassler" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[290,415,535,560]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Xenotrypidae" genus="Xenotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="primaeva">
<emphasis box="[290,415,535,560]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">X. primaeva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<quantity box="[429,586,534,561]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6999999999999997" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="0.16999999999999998" valueMax="0.21" valueMin="0.13">0.13-0.21 mm</quantity>
vs 
<quantity box="[618,775,534,561]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="0.28" valueMax="0.34" valueMin="0.22">0.22-0.34 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Astrova" authorityYear="1965" box="[161,265,566,592]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Constellariidae" genus="Lunaferamita" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cystoporida" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="bassleri">
<emphasis box="[161,265,566,592]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">X. bassleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) as well as in more abundant acanthostyles and abundant diaphragms in autozooecia.
</paragraph>
